03869nam a22006015i 9780674271517DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221993mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742715177 a10.4159/97806742715172doi  a(DE-B1597)614007  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHV851 7aPSY0000002bisacsh1 aClarke-Stewart, Alison, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDaycare :bRevised Edition /cAlison Clarke-Stewart. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (173 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Developing Child00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- t1 / The Problem -- t2 / New Needs -- t3 / History -- t4 / Here and Now -- t5 / Effects on Children -- t6 / Places, Programs, Peers -- t7 / Caregivers -- t8 / Infants and Individuals -- t9 / Finding Good Care -- t10 / Alternatives -- t11 / The Future -- tNotes -- tSuggested Reading -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere are eight million preschoolers whose mothers now work, most of them because of economic necessity. For these mothers the question is not whether to use daycare, but how to choose among the available options in a way that is best for the child. These are just the questions taken up in Daycare, a brief and readable summary of the best information modern “baby science” has to offer about how daycare affects young children and how to tell the difference between daycare that helps and daycare that hurts. On the basis of her own research and a complete review of the most recent daycare studies, Alison Clarke-Stewart concludes that good daycare definitely does not impair the child's development either emotionally or intellectually. Fears that daycare children will fail to develop proper parental attachments and will cling instead to their peers are unfounded; so too are fears that mental growth will be slowed. In fact, there is some evidence that social and intellectual development can be facilitated in good daycare environments. The real question is just what these environments are made of, and here Daycare provides a complete discussion of the necessary ingredients, including a checklist that parents can use to make their own evaluation of any daycare arrangement. This is a book that covers all the practical problems daycare parents must face and suggests ways to solve them that are based not on psychological theory or political conviction but on the facts as we now know them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674271517zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674271517423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674271517/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK